{"title_page": "John McTernan", "text_new": "{{About|the British political strategist|the Australian actor|John McTernan (actor)|the American filmmaker|John McTiernan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n[[File:John McTernan (15580385457).jpg|thumb|McTernan speaking at [[Policy Exchange]], November 2014]]\n'''John McTernan''' (born 1959) is a Conservative [[political strategist]], and commentator. He has been a  political adviser to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and contributes occasional articles to Conservative Home. \n \n\nMcTernan was Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]]'s Director of Political Operations from 2005 to 2007. He then worked on the November 2007 [[Australian Labor Party]] [[2007 Australian federal election|federal election campaign]].<ref name=Guar/> From 2007 to 2010 he was [[Special advisers (UK government)|special adviser]] to two Cabinet Ministers in [[Gordon Brown]]'s Labour Government: first to [[Des Browne]], [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] and [[Secretary of State for Defence]],<ref name=\"Edinburgh Evening News\">{{cite news |last1=Swanson |first1=Ian |title=John McTernan tipped for Alistair Darling seat bid |url= http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/john-mcternan-tipped-for-alistair-darling-seat-bid-1-3628107 |accessdate=23 December 2014 |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=8 December 2014}}</ref> and then to [[Jim Murphy]] MP, the [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] from 2008 until May 2010. From June 2010 to October 2011, he was a columnist at ''[[The Scotsman]]'', and then [[director of communications]] for the Australian Labor prime minister, [[Julia Gillard]], from September 2011 to June 2013.<ref>{{cite news |last=Totaro |first=Paola |title=Julia's master of spin |url= http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-opinion/julias-master-of-spin-20120505-1y5jq.html |accessdate=11 December 2013 |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=6 May 2012}}</ref>\nHe was Chief of Staff to the 2014\u20132015 leader of the [[Scottish Labour Party]], [[Jim Murphy]], who resigned after the Labour Party lost all but one seat in Scotland, including Murphy's, in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].\n\n== Early life ==\nMcTernan was born in London and grew up in Edinburgh, and attended [[Firrhill High School]]. He studied English at the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.scotsman.com/news/uk/john-mcternan-could-succeed-alistair-darling-1-3628297 |date=8 December 2014 |title=John McTernan 'could succeed Alistair Darling' |work=The Scotsman |location= Edinburgh}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Blair and Scottish Labour ===\nMcTernan was Political Secretary/Director of Political Operations at [[10 Downing Street]] for [[Tony Blair]]<ref name=Guar>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/john-mcternan \"John McTernan\"]. London. ''The Guardian''. Retrieved 21 December 2010.</ref> from 2005 to 2007, where he provided [[political management]] and support for the development of the government's [[political strategy]]. In 2007, McTernan was seconded to the [[Scottish Labour Party]] to run its campaign for the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election|May 2007 Scottish Parliament election]].<ref name=\"probe\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/6293191.stm \"Honours probe quiz for No 10 aide\"]. [[BBC News Scotland]]. 24 January 2007.</ref><ref name=\"scotsman2007\">[http://election.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=782&id=80932007 \"Blair aide sent to stem SNP tide\"]. ''[[The Scotsman]]'' (Edinburgh). 16 January 2007.</ref><ref>[http://news.scotsman.com/politics.cfm?id=123682007 \"Now Holyrood election chief quizzed in peerages inquiry\"]. ''The Scotsman'' (Edinburgh). 24 January 2007.</ref>\n\nDuring the 2006\u201307 police investigation into the [[Cash for Honours]] political scandal surrounding the Labour Party, McTernan was twice questioned, [[Right to silence in England and Wales|under caution]], by the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]].<ref name=\"probe\"/><ref name=\"scotsman2007\"/><ref>[http://news.scotsman.com/politics.cfm?id=123682007 \"Now Holyrood election chief quizzed in peerages inquiry\"]. ''[[The Scotsman]]'' (Edinburgh). 24 January 2007.</ref> No criminal charges were ever brought against McTernan or anybody else.\n\nFrom 2007 to 2008 he was Special Adviser to [[Des Browne]], [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] and [[Secretary of State for Defence]].<ref name=\"Edinburgh Evening News\"/> He was [[Special advisers (UK government)|special adviser]] to [[Jim Murphy]] MP, the [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] from 2008 until 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jim Murphy shakes up Scottish Labour\u2019s senior staff team {{!}} LabourList|url=http://labourlist.org/2015/01/jim-murphy-shakes-up-scottish-labours-senior-staff-team/|website=LabourList|accessdate=14 August 2016|date=9 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, while McTernan was employed as a special adviser to the Secretary of State for Scotland, it emerged that in 2002 McTernan had branded Scotland as being \"narrow\" and \"[[racism|racist]]\" during the period he worked for the Scottish Arts Council. In an email to the then Labour [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] [[Karen Gillon]], who was about to make a trip to [[Sweden]], McTernan wrote: \"If you\u2019ve not been to Sweden before, I think you\u2019ll really like it \u2013 it\u2019s the country Scotland would be if it wasn\u2019t narrow, [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]], racist etc. etc. [[Social democracy]] in action.\"<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Scotsman |location=Edinburgh |url= http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/top-stories/des-browne-aide-scotland-is-narrow-presbyterian-and-racist-1-1429086 |title=Des Browne aide: Scotland is narrow, Presbyterian and racist |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> The email was obtained by the London ''[[The Sunday Times|Sunday Times]]'' under [[freedom of information]] legislation.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Australian |location=Sydney |url= http://www.theaustralian.com.au/archive/news/labour-aide-brands-scotland-as-racist/story-e6frg6to-1111115358593?nk=d9c4c90cb94a736f758586fe464af6d9 |title=Labour aide brands Scotland as racist |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |newspaper= The Herald |location= Glasgow |url= http://www.heraldscotland.com/row-over-insulting-email-1.828321 |title=Row over insulting email |date=19 January 2008 |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Work in Australia ===\nIn 2007 he worked on the November 2007 [[Australian Labor Party]] [[2007 Australian federal election|federal election campaign]].<ref name=Guar/>\n\nIn September 2011, he was appointed as communications director to the [[Australian prime minister]], [[Julia Gillard]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Stratton |first=Allegra |title=Ed and Ed learn tough lessons from Blair and Brown |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/sep/27/labour-conference-2011-labour |accessdate=11 December 2013 |work=The Guardian |location= London |date=28 September 2011}}</ref> From February 2011 to October 2011, he was Thinker in Residence at the [[Government of South Australia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Who is John McTernan |newspaper=Adelaide Thinkers in Residence |url=http://www.thinkers.sa.gov.au/thinkers/mcternan/who.aspx |accessdate=25 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150303225510/http://thinkers.sa.gov.au/thinkers/mcternan/who.aspx |archivedate=3 March 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring 2012\u201313, a political scandal erupted over his employment. Accusations were made that Gillard had not attempted to find a suitable Australian candidate for the director of communications post, but had flouted Australia's [[visa (document)|visa]] process to employ John McTernan, a British citizen, on a [[457 visa]] \u2013 a foreign workers scheme which is designed for employers who cannot find local candidates to fill jobs.<ref>{{cite news |author= Grattan, Michelle |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald  |url= http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/457-visa-worker-in-pm-office-20120529-1zhdp.html |title=457 visa worker in PM office |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> When a reporter from Australia's [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] asked McTernan if he was working in Australia on a 457 visa, he replied \"hardly fucking relevant\".<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Australian |location=Sydney |url= http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/investigations/no-trace-of-457-evidence-found/story-fn6tcxar-1226690483361 |title=No trace of 457 evidence found |date=3 August 2013 |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=visa>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-03-05/coalition-taks-aim-at-gillards-communications-director-john-mct/4553386 \"Coalition takes aim at Gillard staffer on 457 visa\"]. [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]. 5 March 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Later career ===\nIn January 2015, McTernan was appointed Chief of Staff to Jim Murphy, then Scottish Labour leader, ahead of the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], and oversaw media and policy in this role.<ref name=heraldscotland-20150109>{{cite news |url= http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13196404.Senior_Blair_aide_to_head_Jim_Murphy_s_backroom_team/ |title= Senior Blair aide to head Jim Murphy's backroom team |author=Magnus Gardham |newspaper=The Herald |location=Glasgow |date=9 January 2015 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |quote=He will work alongside the party's new deputy leader, Kezia Dugdale, and oversee Scottish Labour's media and policy operations.}}</ref>\n\nMcTernan strongly opposed [[Jeremy Corbyn]], the eventual winner, in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 Labour Party leadership election]], describing Corbyn's popularity as a \"strange psychological emotional spasm\". He asserted: \"I can\u2019t see any case for letting him have two minutes in office, let alone two years in office because I think the damage that will be done to the Labour party in that period makes it incredibly hard to recover\".<ref name=spectator-20150729>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Sebastian |url= http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2015/07/john-mcternan-on-labour-leader-who-cares-about-the-grassroots/ |title=John McTernan: If Corbyn wins the Labour leadership, he should be deposed immediately |work=The Spectator |location= London |date=29 July 2015 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20151014>{{cite news |last=McTernan |first=John |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11931162/How-Labour-can-get-rid-of-Jeremy-Corbyn-and-John-McDonnell-in-one-easy-step.html |title=How Labour can get rid of Jeremy Corbyn and John McDonnell - in one easy step |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=14 October 2015 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> The MPs who nominated Corbyn were \"moronic\", according to McTernan.<ref name=independent-20150722>{{cite news |last=Dathan |first=Matt |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/who-are-the-morons-who-nominated-jeremy-corbyn-for-the-labour-leadership-contest-10406527.html |title=So, who are the 'moronic MPs' who nominated Jeremy Corbyn for the Labour leadership contest? |work=The Independent |location= London |date=22 July 2015 |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2016 revelations about [[David Cameron]]'s earlier offshore earnings, and Corbyn's call for an investigation,<ref name=guardian-20160405>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/apr/05/david-cameron-must-come-clean-on-tax-says-jeremy-corbyn-panama-papers |title=David Cameron must come clean on tax, says Jeremy Corbyn |newspaper=The Guardian |location= London |date=5 April 2016 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> McTernan argued in his ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' column that [[tax avoidance]] is an expression of basic British freedoms.<ref name=telegraph-20160405>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/05/tax-avoidance-is-an-expression-of-basic-british-freedoms/ |title=Tax avoidance is an expression of basic British freedoms |author=John McTernan |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=5 April 2016 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016 McTernan joined the policy and media advice agency Westminster Policy Institute as an associate.<ref name=prw-20160204>{{cite news |url= http://www.prweek.com/article/1382245/former-blair-adviser-john-mcternan-joins-public-affairs-agency |title=Former Blair adviser John McTernan joins public affairs agency |author=Ian Griggs |work=PR Week |date=4 February 2016 |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> He continued to write a regular column for ''The Daily Telegraph''.<ref name=telegraph->{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/authors/john-mcternan/ |title=John McTernan |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, McTernan bet blogger [[Stuart Campbell (game journalist)|Stuart Campbell]] $100 on a [[Hillary Clinton|Clinton]] victory in the [[2016 US presidential election]], which he lost. Campbell has claimed that McTernan failed to honour the bet, and Campbell has taken court action against him.<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/homenews/14932790.Political_blogger_takes_court_action_against_former_Blair_aide_over_Clinton_bet/ \"Political blogger takes court action against former Blair aide over Clinton bet\"]. ''The Scotsman''. 28 November 2016.</ref>\n\nIn August 2017 McTernan joined the Labour Party left-wing pressure group [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]], set up to support [[Jeremy Corbyn|Jeremy Corbyn's]] leadership. McTernan had previously been a critic of Momentum and of Corbyn.<ref name=\"Mairs\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/88199/watch-arch-blairite-john-mcternan-joins-momentum |title=Arch-Blairite John McTernan joins Momentum |last=Mairs |first=Nicholas |date=13 August 2017 |website=PoliticsHome |access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, John McTernan was asked if he still defends the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]]. He responded in the affirmative: \"Any war against a fascist dictator is a good war.\"<ref name=\"Novara Media\">{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LADZxyxllUQ |title=Is Centrism Dead?|date=22 October 2018}}</ref> He went on to compare the war in Iraq to [[the Falklands War]], [[the Second World War]] and [[the Spanish Civil War]]. \"As my Kurdish say 'We never ask why did you invade, we ask why did you take so long?',\" said McTernan. He went on to argue that [[Brexit]] was a result of a lack of a humanitarian intervention in the [[Syrian Civil War]] because it would have prevented the refugee crisis.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110513034149/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/newsfront.aspx?sectionid=17858&IsTopic=1 John McTernan columns] for ''[[The Scotsman]]''\n* [http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/author/johnmcternan1/ ''Daily Telegraph'' blog]\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{British special advisers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McTernan, John}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:British political consultants]]\n[[Category:British special advisers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Logie Award winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Firrhill High School]]\n[[Category:Politicians from London]]\n[[Category:Scottish Labour Party politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the British political strategist|the Australian actor|John McTernan (actor)|the American filmmaker|John McTiernan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n[[File:John McTernan (15580385457).jpg|thumb|McTernan speaking at [[Policy Exchange]], November 2014]]\n'''John McTernan''' (born 1959) is a British [[political strategist]] and commentator. He has been a  political adviser to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].\n\nMcTernan was Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]]'s Director of Political Operations from 2005 to 2007. He then worked on the November 2007 [[Australian Labor Party]] [[2007 Australian federal election|federal election campaign]].<ref name=Guar/> From 2007 to 2010 he was [[Special advisers (UK government)|special adviser]] to two Cabinet Ministers in [[Gordon Brown]]'s Labour Government: first to [[Des Browne]], [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] and [[Secretary of State for Defence]],<ref name=\"Edinburgh Evening News\">{{cite news |last1=Swanson |first1=Ian |title=John McTernan tipped for Alistair Darling seat bid |url= http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/john-mcternan-tipped-for-alistair-darling-seat-bid-1-3628107 |accessdate=23 December 2014 |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=8 December 2014}}</ref> and then to [[Jim Murphy]] MP, the [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] from 2008 until May 2010. From June 2010 to October 2011, he was a columnist at ''[[The Scotsman]]'', and then [[director of communications]] for the Australian Labor prime minister, [[Julia Gillard]], from September 2011 to June 2013.<ref>{{cite news |last=Totaro |first=Paola |title=Julia's master of spin |url= http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-opinion/julias-master-of-spin-20120505-1y5jq.html |accessdate=11 December 2013 |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=6 May 2012}}</ref>\nHe was Chief of Staff to the 2014\u20132015 leader of the [[Scottish Labour Party]], [[Jim Murphy]], who resigned after the Labour Party lost all but one seat in Scotland, including Murphy's, in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].\n\n== Early life ==\nMcTernan was born in London and grew up in Edinburgh, and attended [[Firrhill High School]]. He studied English at the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.scotsman.com/news/uk/john-mcternan-could-succeed-alistair-darling-1-3628297 |date=8 December 2014 |title=John McTernan 'could succeed Alistair Darling' |work=The Scotsman |location= Edinburgh}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Blair and Scottish Labour ===\nMcTernan was Political Secretary/Director of Political Operations at [[10 Downing Street]] for [[Tony Blair]]<ref name=Guar>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/john-mcternan \"John McTernan\"]. London. ''The Guardian''. Retrieved 21 December 2010.</ref> from 2005 to 2007, where he provided [[political management]] and support for the development of the government's [[political strategy]]. In 2007, McTernan was seconded to the [[Scottish Labour Party]] to run its campaign for the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election|May 2007 Scottish Parliament election]].<ref name=\"probe\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/6293191.stm \"Honours probe quiz for No 10 aide\"]. [[BBC News Scotland]]. 24 January 2007.</ref><ref name=\"scotsman2007\">[http://election.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=782&id=80932007 \"Blair aide sent to stem SNP tide\"]. ''[[The Scotsman]]'' (Edinburgh). 16 January 2007.</ref><ref>[http://news.scotsman.com/politics.cfm?id=123682007 \"Now Holyrood election chief quizzed in peerages inquiry\"]. ''The Scotsman'' (Edinburgh). 24 January 2007.</ref>\n\nDuring the 2006\u201307 police investigation into the [[Cash for Honours]] political scandal surrounding the Labour Party, McTernan was twice questioned, [[Right to silence in England and Wales|under caution]], by the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]].<ref name=\"probe\"/><ref name=\"scotsman2007\"/><ref>[http://news.scotsman.com/politics.cfm?id=123682007 \"Now Holyrood election chief quizzed in peerages inquiry\"]. ''[[The Scotsman]]'' (Edinburgh). 24 January 2007.</ref> No criminal charges were ever brought against McTernan or anybody else.\n\nFrom 2007 to 2008 he was Special Adviser to [[Des Browne]], [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] and [[Secretary of State for Defence]].<ref name=\"Edinburgh Evening News\"/> He was [[Special advisers (UK government)|special adviser]] to [[Jim Murphy]] MP, the [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] from 2008 until 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jim Murphy shakes up Scottish Labour\u2019s senior staff team {{!}} LabourList|url=http://labourlist.org/2015/01/jim-murphy-shakes-up-scottish-labours-senior-staff-team/|website=LabourList|accessdate=14 August 2016|date=9 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, while McTernan was employed as a special adviser to the Secretary of State for Scotland, it emerged that in 2002 McTernan had branded Scotland as being \"narrow\" and \"[[racism|racist]]\" during the period he worked for the Scottish Arts Council. In an email to the then Labour [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] [[Karen Gillon]], who was about to make a trip to [[Sweden]], McTernan wrote: \"If you\u2019ve not been to Sweden before, I think you\u2019ll really like it \u2013 it\u2019s the country Scotland would be if it wasn\u2019t narrow, [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]], racist etc. etc. [[Social democracy]] in action.\"<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Scotsman |location=Edinburgh |url= http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/top-stories/des-browne-aide-scotland-is-narrow-presbyterian-and-racist-1-1429086 |title=Des Browne aide: Scotland is narrow, Presbyterian and racist |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> The email was obtained by the London ''[[The Sunday Times|Sunday Times]]'' under [[freedom of information]] legislation.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Australian |location=Sydney |url= http://www.theaustralian.com.au/archive/news/labour-aide-brands-scotland-as-racist/story-e6frg6to-1111115358593?nk=d9c4c90cb94a736f758586fe464af6d9 |title=Labour aide brands Scotland as racist |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |newspaper= The Herald |location= Glasgow |url= http://www.heraldscotland.com/row-over-insulting-email-1.828321 |title=Row over insulting email |date=19 January 2008 |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Work in Australia ===\nIn 2007 he worked on the November 2007 [[Australian Labor Party]] [[2007 Australian federal election|federal election campaign]].<ref name=Guar/>\n\nIn September 2011, he was appointed as communications director to the [[Australian prime minister]], [[Julia Gillard]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Stratton |first=Allegra |title=Ed and Ed learn tough lessons from Blair and Brown |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/sep/27/labour-conference-2011-labour |accessdate=11 December 2013 |work=The Guardian |location= London |date=28 September 2011}}</ref> From February 2011 to October 2011, he was Thinker in Residence at the [[Government of South Australia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Who is John McTernan |newspaper=Adelaide Thinkers in Residence |url=http://www.thinkers.sa.gov.au/thinkers/mcternan/who.aspx |accessdate=25 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150303225510/http://thinkers.sa.gov.au/thinkers/mcternan/who.aspx |archivedate=3 March 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring 2012\u201313, a political scandal erupted over his employment. Accusations were made that Gillard had not attempted to find a suitable Australian candidate for the director of communications post, but had flouted Australia's [[visa (document)|visa]] process to employ John McTernan, a British citizen, on a [[457 visa]] \u2013 a foreign workers scheme which is designed for employers who cannot find local candidates to fill jobs.<ref>{{cite news |author= Grattan, Michelle |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald  |url= http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/457-visa-worker-in-pm-office-20120529-1zhdp.html |title=457 visa worker in PM office |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> When a reporter from Australia's [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] asked McTernan if he was working in Australia on a 457 visa, he replied \"hardly fucking relevant\".<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Australian |location=Sydney |url= http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/investigations/no-trace-of-457-evidence-found/story-fn6tcxar-1226690483361 |title=No trace of 457 evidence found |date=3 August 2013 |accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=visa>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-03-05/coalition-taks-aim-at-gillards-communications-director-john-mct/4553386 \"Coalition takes aim at Gillard staffer on 457 visa\"]. [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]. 5 March 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Later career ===\nIn January 2015, McTernan was appointed Chief of Staff to Jim Murphy, then Scottish Labour leader, ahead of the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], and oversaw media and policy in this role.<ref name=heraldscotland-20150109>{{cite news |url= http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13196404.Senior_Blair_aide_to_head_Jim_Murphy_s_backroom_team/ |title= Senior Blair aide to head Jim Murphy's backroom team |author=Magnus Gardham |newspaper=The Herald |location=Glasgow |date=9 January 2015 |accessdate=8 April 2016 |quote=He will work alongside the party's new deputy leader, Kezia Dugdale, and oversee Scottish Labour's media and policy operations.}}</ref>\n\nMcTernan strongly opposed [[Jeremy Corbyn]], the eventual winner, in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 Labour Party leadership election]], describing Corbyn's popularity as a \"strange psychological emotional spasm\". He asserted: \"I can\u2019t see any case for letting him have two minutes in office, let alone two years in office because I think the damage that will be done to the Labour party in that period makes it incredibly hard to recover\".<ref name=spectator-20150729>{{cite news |last=Payne |first=Sebastian |url= http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2015/07/john-mcternan-on-labour-leader-who-cares-about-the-grassroots/ |title=John McTernan: If Corbyn wins the Labour leadership, he should be deposed immediately |work=The Spectator |location= London |date=29 July 2015 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20151014>{{cite news |last=McTernan |first=John |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11931162/How-Labour-can-get-rid-of-Jeremy-Corbyn-and-John-McDonnell-in-one-easy-step.html |title=How Labour can get rid of Jeremy Corbyn and John McDonnell - in one easy step |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=14 October 2015 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> The MPs who nominated Corbyn were \"moronic\", according to McTernan.<ref name=independent-20150722>{{cite news |last=Dathan |first=Matt |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/who-are-the-morons-who-nominated-jeremy-corbyn-for-the-labour-leadership-contest-10406527.html |title=So, who are the 'moronic MPs' who nominated Jeremy Corbyn for the Labour leadership contest? |work=The Independent |location= London |date=22 July 2015 |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2016 revelations about [[David Cameron]]'s earlier offshore earnings, and Corbyn's call for an investigation,<ref name=guardian-20160405>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/apr/05/david-cameron-must-come-clean-on-tax-says-jeremy-corbyn-panama-papers |title=David Cameron must come clean on tax, says Jeremy Corbyn |newspaper=The Guardian |location= London |date=5 April 2016 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> McTernan argued in his ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' column that [[tax avoidance]] is an expression of basic British freedoms.<ref name=telegraph-20160405>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/05/tax-avoidance-is-an-expression-of-basic-british-freedoms/ |title=Tax avoidance is an expression of basic British freedoms |author=John McTernan |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=5 April 2016 |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016 McTernan joined the policy and media advice agency Westminster Policy Institute as an associate.<ref name=prw-20160204>{{cite news |url= http://www.prweek.com/article/1382245/former-blair-adviser-john-mcternan-joins-public-affairs-agency |title=Former Blair adviser John McTernan joins public affairs agency |author=Ian Griggs |work=PR Week |date=4 February 2016 |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> He continued to write a regular column for ''The Daily Telegraph''.<ref name=telegraph->{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/authors/john-mcternan/ |title=John McTernan |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, McTernan bet blogger [[Stuart Campbell (game journalist)|Stuart Campbell]] $100 on a [[Hillary Clinton|Clinton]] victory in the [[2016 US presidential election]], which he lost. Campbell has claimed that McTernan failed to honour the bet, and Campbell has taken court action against him.<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/homenews/14932790.Political_blogger_takes_court_action_against_former_Blair_aide_over_Clinton_bet/ \"Political blogger takes court action against former Blair aide over Clinton bet\"]. ''The Scotsman''. 28 November 2016.</ref>\n\nIn August 2017 McTernan joined the Labour Party left-wing pressure group [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]], set up to support [[Jeremy Corbyn|Jeremy Corbyn's]] leadership. McTernan had previously been a critic of Momentum and of Corbyn.<ref name=\"Mairs\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/88199/watch-arch-blairite-john-mcternan-joins-momentum |title=Arch-Blairite John McTernan joins Momentum |last=Mairs |first=Nicholas |date=13 August 2017 |website=PoliticsHome |access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, John McTernan was asked if he still defends the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]]. He responded in the affirmative: \"Any war against a fascist dictator is a good war.\"<ref name=\"Novara Media\">{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LADZxyxllUQ |title=Is Centrism Dead?|date=22 October 2018}}</ref> He went on to compare the war in Iraq to [[the Falklands War]], [[the Second World War]] and [[the Spanish Civil War]]. \"As my Kurdish say 'We never ask why did you invade, we ask why did you take so long?',\" said McTernan. He went on to argue that [[Brexit]] was a result of a lack of a humanitarian intervention in the [[Syrian Civil War]] because it would have prevented the refugee crisis.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110513034149/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/newsfront.aspx?sectionid=17858&IsTopic=1 John McTernan columns] for ''[[The Scotsman]]''\n* [http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/author/johnmcternan1/ ''Daily Telegraph'' blog]\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{British special advisers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McTernan, John}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:British political consultants]]\n[[Category:British special advisers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Logie Award winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Firrhill High School]]\n[[Category:Politicians from London]]\n[[Category:Scottish Labour Party politicians]]\n", "name_user": "92.10.175.45", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_McTernan"}
{"title_page": "Steve Horvath", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Steve Horvath\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| other_names = \n| known_for   = developing the [[epigenetic clock]] (Horvath clock) and [[weighted correlation network analysis]].\n}}\n'''Steve Horvath''' is a German/American aging researcher, geneticist, and [[biostatistician]]. He is a professor at the [[University of California Los Angeles]] known for developing the [[Epigenetic clock|Horvath aging clock]], which is a highly accurate molecular [[Biomarkers of aging|biomarker of aging]], and for developing [[weighted correlation network analysis]].\nThe recipient of several research awards he has studied [[Biomarkers of aging|genomic biomarkers of aging]], the [[senescence|aging process]], and many age related diseases/conditions.\n[[File:Steve Horvath, UCLA professor, presenting a talk June 2015.jpg|thumb|Steve Horvath, UCLA professor, presenting a talk June 2015]]\n\n== Background ==\nHorvath was born in [[Frankfurt]], [[Germany]].<ref name=\"Gibbs2014\"/> He received his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in mathematics at the [[University of North Carolina]] in 1995 and his [[Doctor of Science|Sc.D.]] in biostatistics at [[Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health|Harvard]] in 2000.<ref name=\"Gibbs2014\"/>  In 2000 Horvath joined the faculty of the [[University of California| University of California, Los Angeles]], where he is a Professor of [[human genetics]] at the David Geffen School of Medicine at [[UCLA]] and of [[biostatistics]] at the [[UCLA]] Fielding School of Public Health.<ref name=\"Gibbs2014\"/>\n\n== Work on the epigenetic clock ==\nHorvath's development of the [[DNA methylation]] based age estimation method known as [[epigenetic clock]]  was featured in Nature magazine.<ref name=\"Gibbs2014\"/>\nIn 2011 Horvath co-authored the first article that described an age estimation method based on DNA methylation levels from saliva.<ref name=\"Bocklandt2011\"/> In 2013 Horvath published a single author article on a multi-tissue age estimation method that applies to all nucleated cells, tissues, and organs.<ref name=\"Horvath2013\"/><ref name=\"Gibbs2014\"/> This discovery, known as the [[Epigenetic clock|Horvath clock]], was unexpected because cell types differ in terms of their DNA methylation patterns and age related DNA methylation changes tend to be tissue specific.<ref name=\"Gibbs2014\"/> In his article, he demonstrated that estimated age, also referred to as DNA methylation age, has the following properties: it is close to zero for embryonic and [[induced pluripotent stem cell]]s, it correlates with cell [[Subculture (biology)#Passage number|passage number]]; it gives rise to a highly heritable measure of age acceleration; and it is applicable to chimpanzees.<ref name=\"Horvath2013\"/> \nSince the Horvath clock allows one to contrast the ages of different tissues from the same individuals, it can be used to identify tissues that show evidence of increased or decreased age.<ref name=\"Horvath2015cerebellum\"/>\n\n===Age related conditions and phenotypes===\nHorvath co-authored the first articles demonstrating that DNA methylation age predicts life-expectancy <ref name=\"Marioni2015mortality\"/><ref name=\"Horvath2015centenarian\"/><ref name=\"Chen2016\"/> and is positively associated with [[obesity]],<ref name=\"Horvath2014obesity\"/> [[HIV]] infection,<ref name=\"Horvath2015HIV\"/> [[Alzheimer's disease]],<ref name=\"Levine2015\"/> cognitive decline,<ref name=\"Marioni2015fitness\"/> [[Parkinson's disease]],<ref name=\"Horvath2015Parkinson\">{{cite journal | last1 = Horvath | first1 = S | year = 2015 | title = Increased epigenetic age and granulocyte counts in the blood of Parkinson's disease patients.| url = http://www.impactaging.com/papers/v7/n12/full/100859.html| journal = Aging | volume=7| issue =12| pages =  1130\u201342| doi = 10.18632/aging.100859| pmid= 26655927 | pmc=4712337}}</ref> [[Huntington's disease]],<ref name=\"Horvath2016HD\"/> early [[menopause]],<ref name=\"Levine2016menopause\"/> and [[Werner syndrome]].<ref name=\"Maierhofer2017Werner\"/>\n\n===Genetics of aging===\nHorvath published the first article demonstrating that trisomy 21 ([[Down syndrome]]) is associated with strong epigenetic age acceleration effects in both blood and brain tissue.<ref name=\"Horvath2015DownSyndrome\"/> \nUsing [[Genome-wide association study|genome-wide association studies]], Horvath's team identified the first genetic markers (SNPs) that exhibit genome-wide significant associations with epigenetic aging rates.<ref name=\"Lu2016\"/><ref name=\"Lu2017\"/>\nIn particular, the first genome-wide significant genetic loci associated with epigenetic aging rates in blood notably the telomerase reverse transcriptase gene ([[Telomerase reverse transcriptase|TERT]]) locus.<ref name=\"LuGWAS2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Lu |first1=Ake T. |last2=Xue |first2=Luting |last3=Salfati |first3=Elias L. |last4=Chen |first4=Brian H. |last5=Ferrucci |first5=Luigi |last6=Levy |first6=Daniel |last7=Joehanes |first7=Roby |last8=Murabito |first8=Joanne M. |last9=Kiel |first9=Douglas P. |last10=Tsai |first10=Pei-Chien |last11=Yet |first11=Idil |last12=Bell |first12=Jordana T. |last13=Mangino |first13=Massimo |last14=Tanaka |first14=Toshiko |last15=McRae |first15=Allan F. |last16=Marioni |first16=Riccardo E. |last17=Visscher |first17=Peter M. |last18=Wray |first18=Naomi R. |last19=Deary |first19=Ian J. |last20=Levine |first20=Morgan E. |last21=Quach |first21=Austin |last22=Assimes |first22=Themistocles |last23=Tsao |first23=Philip S. |last24=Absher |first24=Devin |last25=Stewart |first25=James D. |last26=Li |first26=Yun |last27=Reiner |first27=Alex P. |last28=Hou |first28=Lifang |last29=Baccarelli |first29=Andrea A. |last30=Whitsel |first30=Eric A. |last31=Aviv |first31=Abraham |last32=Cardona |first32=Alexia |last33=Day |first33=Felix R. |last34=Wareham |first34=Nicholas J. |last35=Perry |first35=John R. B. |last36=Ong |first36=Ken K. |last37=Raj |first37=Kenneth |last38=Lunetta |first38=Kathryn L. |last39=Horvath |first39=Steve |title=GWAS of epigenetic aging rates in blood reveals a critical role for TERT |journal=Nature Communications |date=26 January 2018 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=387 |doi=10.1038/s41467-017-02697-5 |pmid=29374233 |pmc=5786029 |bibcode=2018NatCo...9..387L }}</ref>\n\nAs part of this work, his team uncovered a paradoxical relationship: genetic variants associated with longer leukocyte telomere length in the TERT gene paradoxically confer higher epigenetic age acceleration in blood.<ref name=\"LuGWAS2018\"/>\n\n===Work in biodemography===\nHorvath proposed that slower epigenetic aging rates could explain the mortality advantage of women and the [[Hispanic paradox|Hispanic mortality paradox]].<ref name=\"Horvath2016Race\">{{cite journal |last1=Horvath |first1=Steve |last2=Gurven |first2=Michael |last3=Levine |first3=Morgan E. |last4=Trumble |first4=Benjamin C. |last5=Kaplan |first5=Hillard |last6=Allayee |first6=Hooman |last7=Ritz |first7=Beate R. |last8=Chen |first8=Brian |last9=Lu |first9=Ake T. |last10=Rickabaugh |first10=Tammy M. |last11=Jamieson |first11=Beth D. |last12=Sun |first12=Dianjianyi |last13=Li |first13=Shengxu |last14=Chen |first14=Wei |last15=Quintana-Murci |first15=Lluis |last16=Fagny |first16=Maud |last17=Kobor |first17=Michael S. |last18=Tsao |first18=Philip S. |last19=Reiner |first19=Alexander P. |last20=Edlefsen |first20=Kerstin L. |last21=Absher |first21=Devin |last22=Assimes |first22=Themistocles L. |title=An epigenetic clock analysis of race/ethnicity, sex, and coronary heart disease |journal=Genome Biology |date=11 August 2016 |volume=17 |issue=1 |pages=171 |doi=10.1186/s13059-016-1030-0 |pmid=27511193 |pmc=4980791 }}</ref>\n\n===Lifestyle factors and nutrition===\nHorvath published the first large scale study of the effect of lifestyle factors on epigenetic aging rates.<ref name=\"Quach2017\">{{cite journal |last1=Quach |first1=Austin |last2=Levine |first2=Morgan E. |last3=Tanaka |first3=Toshiko |last4=Lu |first4=Ake T. |last5=Chen |first5=Brian H. |last6=Ferrucci |first6=Luigi |last7=Ritz |first7=Beate |last8=Bandinelli |first8=Stefania |last9=Neuhouser |first9=Marian L. |last10=Beasley |first10=Jeannette M. |last11=Snetselaar |first11=Linda |last12=Wallace |first12=Robert B. |last13=Tsao |first13=Philip S. |last14=Absher |first14=Devin |last15=Assimes |first15=Themistocles L. |last16=Stewart |first16=James D. |last17=Li |first17=Yun |last18=Hou |first18=Lifang |last19=Baccarelli |first19=Andrea A. |last20=Whitsel |first20=Eric A. |last21=Horvath |first21=Steve |title=Epigenetic clock analysis of diet, exercise, education, and lifestyle factors |journal=Aging |date=14 February 2017 |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=419\u2013446 |doi=10.18632/aging.101168 |pmid=28198702 |pmc=5361673 }}</ref>\n\nThese cross sectional of epigenetic aging rates in blood confirm the conventional wisdom regarding the benefits of education, eating a high plant diet with lean meats, moderate alcohol consumption, physical activity and the risks associated with [[Metabolic syndromemetablic syndrome|metabolic syndrome]].\n\n===Epigenetic clock theory of aging===\nHorvath and Raj proposed an epigenetic clock theory of aging<ref name=\"HorvathRaj2018\">{{cite journal |last1=Horvath |first1=Steve |last2=Raj |first2=Kenneth |title=DNA methylation-based biomarkers and the epigenetic clock theory of ageing |journal=Nature Reviews Genetics |date=11 April 2018 |volume=19 |issue=6 |pages=371\u2013384 |doi=10.1038/s41576-018-0004-3 |pmid=29643443 |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/c69620917b6063f85623ada8ded556c8f578f529 }}</ref> which views biological aging as an unintended consequence of both developmental programs and maintenance program, the molecular footprints of which give rise to DNA methylation age estimators. DNAm age is viewed as a proximal readout of a collection of innate ageing processes that conspire with other, independent root causes of aging, to the detriment of tissue function.<ref name=\"HorvathRaj2018\"/>\n\n==Weighted correlation network analysis==\nHorvath and members of his lab developed a widely used [[Systems biology|systems biological]] data mining technique known as [[weighted correlation network analysis]].<ref name=\"Zhang2005\"/><ref name=\"Horvath2006\"/><ref name=\"Langfelder2008\"/> He published a book on weighted network analysis and genomic applications.<ref name=\"Horvath2011\"/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nHorvath has won several awards for his work on the epigenetic clock.\n* 2017 Allen Distinguished Investigator award for clock studies in vertebrates <ref name=\"PaulGAllen2017\"/>\n* 2019 Open Philanthropy Project award for mechanistic studies of the epigenetic clock <ref name=\"OpenPhilanthropyHorvath\"/>\n* 2019 Schober Award for outstanding and innovative research in the field of ageing <ref name=\"SchoberHorvath\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Bocklandt2011\">{{cite journal | last1 = Bocklandt | first1 = S | last2 = Lin | first2 = W | last3 = Sehl | first3 = ME | last4 = S\u00e1nchez | first4 = FJ | last5 = Sinsheimer | first5 = JS | last6 = Horvath | first6 = S | last7 = Vilain | first7 = E | year = 2011 | title = Epigenetic Predictor of Age | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 6 | issue = 6| page = e14821 | pmid = 21731603 | doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0014821 | pmc=3120753| bibcode = 2011PLoSO...614821B }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Horvath2013\">{{cite journal | last1 = Horvath | first1 = S | year = 2013 | title = DNA methylation age of human tissues and cell types | url = | journal = Genome Biology | volume = 14| issue = 10 | page = R115 | doi = 10.1186/gb-2013-14-10-r115 | pmid=24138928 | pmc=4015143}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Horvath2015centenarian\">{{cite journal | last1 = Horvath | first1 = S  | date = 2015 | title = Decreased epigenetic age of PBMCs from Italian s