/DANCINGD/DANCINGD.html | title = Dancing Daze | work = Australian Television Memorabilia Guide | publisher = Nodette Enterprises Pty Ltd | year = 2003 | accessdate = 6 August 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110717114644/http://tvmem.com/DATA/A-Z/D/DANCINGD/DANCINGD.html | archivedate = 17 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AusChartsR\">{{cite web | url = http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Rockmelons | title = Discography Rockmelons | publisher = Hung Medien | work = Australian charts portal | accessdate =24 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIA1989\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1989 |title=ARIA Awards \u2013 History: Winners by Year: 1989: 3rd Annual ARIA Awards |publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) |accessdate=23 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111011200102/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1989 |archivedate=11 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"McFAF\">McFarlane [https://web.archive.org/web/20040803090539/http://www.whammo.com.au/encyclopedia.asp?articleid=8 'Absent Friends'] entry. Retrieved 24 July 2010.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AusChartsAF\">{{cite web | url = http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Absent+Friends | title = Discography Absent Friends | publisher = Hung Medien | work = Australian charts portal | accessdate =24 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news | title = Best female singer Wendy Matthews | newspaper = [[Rolling Stone Australia|Rolling Stone]] | publisher = [[ACP Magazines]] | last1 = Taylor | first1 = Greg | year = 1990}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARDbNC\">{{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121006095038/http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/n/noelscowards.html | url = http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/n/noelscowards.html | title = Noel's Cowards | publisher = Australian Rock Database. Passagen.se (Magnus Holmgren) | first1 = Magnus | last1 = Holmgren | first2 = Stefan | last2 = Warnqvist | archivedate = 6 October 2012 | accessdate = 14 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIA1991\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1991 |title=ARIA Awards \u2013 History: Winners by Year: 1991: 5th Annual ARIA Awards |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) |accessdate=29 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608063024/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1991 |archivedate=8 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AusCharts\">{{cite web | url = http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Wendy+Matthews | title = Discography Wendy Matthews | publisher = Hung Medien | work = Australian charts portal | accessdate =29 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIA1992\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1992 |title=ARIA Awards \u2013 History: Winners by Year: 1992: 6th Annual ARIA Awards |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) |accessdate=29 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235813/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1992 |archivedate=26 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIA1993\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1993 |title=ARIA Awards \u2013 History: Winners by Year: 1993: 7th Annual ARIA Awards |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) |accessdate=29 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927120818/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1993 |archivedate=27 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Flynn\">{{cite web | url = http://www.muff.com.au/2006/oz_cinema.htm | title = Australian Cult Cinema \u2013 Part 5: The Frank Howson/Boulevard Films Legacy | publisher = [[Melbourne Underground Film Festival]] | date = 6\u201316 July 2006 | accessdate = 1 August 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110227033242/http://www.muff.com.au/2006/oz_cinema.htm | archivedate = 27 February 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIA1994\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1994 |title=ARIA Awards \u2013 History: Winners by Year: 1994: 8th Annual ARIA Awards |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) |accessdate=29 July 2010 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"APRAWin1995\">{{cite web|url=http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/1995Winners.aspx |title=1995 Winners \u2013 APRA Music Awards |publisher=Australasian Performing Right Association (APRA) |accessdate=31 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308005511/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/1995Winners.aspx |archivedate=8 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIAWM\">{{cite web | url = http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-artist.php?letter=W&artist=Wendy%20Matthews | title = ARIA Awards 2009 : History: Winners by Artist: Wendy Matthews | publisher = Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) | accessdate = 31 July 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIACred1999\">{{cite web | url = http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-albums-1999.htm | title = ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 1999 Albums | publisher = Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) | accessdate =29 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARDbOR\">{{cite web | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120907182115/http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/comp/olympicrecord.html | url = http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/comp/olympicrecord.html | work = | title = Olympic Record | publisher = Australian Rock Database. Passagen.se (Magnus Holmgren) | first1 = Magnus | last1 = Holmgren | archivedate = 7 September 2012 | accessdate =14 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NLACafe\">{{cite web | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.cs-ma-NAMO~3732 | title = Matthews, Wendy | work = [[Music Australia]] | publisher = [[National Library of Australia]] | date = 28 June 2004 | accessdate =9 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Cafe\">{{cite web | url = http://www.wendymatthews.com.au/newsapraug2004.htm | title = Caf\u00e9 Naturale | publisher = Wendy Matthews | accessdate = 6 August 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110217052157/http://www.wendymatthews.com.au/newsapraug2004.htm | archivedate = 17 February 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tripp\">{{cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/local/audio/2010/06/03/2916790.htm | title = Neil Pigot, Bobby Rydell and Wendy Matthews | last1 = Tripp | first1 = Amber | publisher = Australian Broadcasting Corporation | date = 3 June 2010 | accessdate =31 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIA1995\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1995 |title=ARIA Awards \u2013 History: Winners by Year: 1995: 9th Annual ARIA Awards |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) |accessdate=1 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235646/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1995 |archivedate=26 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIA1997\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1997 |title=ARIA Awards \u2013 History: Winners by Year: 1997: 11th Annual ARIA Awards |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) |accessdate=1 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235734/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1997 |archivedate=26 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIA1998\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1998 |title=ARIA Awards \u2013 History: Winners by Year: 1998: 12th Annual ARIA Awards |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) |accessdate=1 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927121049/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=1998 |archivedate=27 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIA2001\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=2001 |title=ARIA Awards \u2013 History: Winners by Year: 2001: 15th Annual ARIA Awards |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) |accessdate=1 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235727/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-year.php?year=2001 |archivedate=26 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIAAF\">{{cite web | url = http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-artist.php?letter=A&artist=Absent%20Friends | title = ARIA Awards 2009 : History: Winners by Artist: Absent Friends | publisher = Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) | accessdate = 1 August 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIAAR\">{{cite web | url = http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-artist.php?letter=R&artist=Rockmelons | title = ARIA Awards 2009 : History: Winners by Artist: Rockmelons | publisher = Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) | accessdate = 1 August 2010 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIAAVar\">{{cite web | url = http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history-by-artist.php?letter=V&artist=Various | title = ARIA Awards 2009 : History: Winners by Artist: Various | publisher = Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) | accessdate = 1 August 2010 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Stringer\">{{cite web | url = http://www.tvmem.com/DATA/A-Z/S/STRINGER/STRINGER.html | title = Stringer | work = Australian Television Memorabilia Guide | publisher = Nodette Enterprises Pty Ltd | year = 2003 | accessdate = 1 August 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110724084057/http://www.tvmem.com/DATA/A-Z/S/STRINGER/STRINGER.html | archivedate = 24 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Mo1991\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moawards.com/?page_id=601 |title=Winners \u2013 16th Mo Awards 1991 |publisher=Australian Entertainment 'MO' Awards Inc |accessdate=1 August 2010 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307142707/http://www.moawards.com/?page_id=601 |archivedate=7 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ARIAHoFAAP\">{{Cite news | title = Old talent time: ARIA honours music legends | last1 = Australian Association Press (AAP) | authorlink1 = Australian Associated Press | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/10/28/3050226.htm?site=sydney | publisher = [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC) |  date = 28 October 2010 | accessdate =28 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Treuen\">{{Cite news | title = ARIA Hall of Fame celebrates music's loved ones | url = http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-news/industry/2010/10/28/aria-hall-of-fame-celebrates-musics-loved-ones/ | last1 = Treuen | first1 = Jason | publisher = [[The Music Network]] (Peer Group Media) | date = 28 October 2010 | accessdate =29 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Street\">{{Cite news | url = http://www.timeoutsydney.com.au/music/models-inducted-into-aria-hall-of-fame.aspx | title = Models inducted into ARIA Hall of Fame | last1 = Street | first1 = Andrew P | publisher = Time Out Group | newspaper = Time Out | date = 25 October 2010 | accessdate = 28 October 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.is/20121230185944/http://www.timeoutsydney.com.au/music/models-inducted-into-aria-hall-of-fame.aspx | archivedate = 30 December 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Pepper\">{{Cite news | url = http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/the-models-james-freud-dead-20101104-17f7r.html | title = Models' frontman tragedy: James Freud takes own life | last1 = Pepper | first1 = Daile | last2 = Murfett | first2 = Andrew | publisher = Fairfax Media | newspaper = The Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate =4 November 2010 | date=4 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.wendymatthews.com/|Wendy Matthews}}\n* [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p102770/biography|pure_url=yes}} Wendy Matthews biography] at [[Allmusic]]\n*{{IMDb name|0560215|Wendy Matthews}}\n{{Wendy Joan Matthews}}\n{{Models (band)}}\n{{ARIA Award for Breakthrough Artist}}\n{{ARIA Award for Single of the Year 1990s}}\n{{ARIA Award for Best Female Artist 1990s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matthews, Wendy}}\n[[Category:Wendy Matthews|*]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Abenaki people]]\n[[Category:Absent Friends (band) members]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Australian female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Canadian descent]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:Canadian female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Spanish descent]] \n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Models (band) members]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Sydney]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|image = |\n|name = Wendy Matthews\n|background = solo_singer\n|birth_name = Wendy Joan Matthews\n|alias =\n|birth_date = {{birth year and age|1960}}\n|birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada\n|label = [[Alfa Records|Alfa]], [[ABC Commercial|ABC]], [[RooArt|rooART]], [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]], [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]], [[Warner Music Australasia|Warner]]\n|instrument = [[Singing|Vocals]]\n|genre = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n|occupation = [[Singer-songwriter]], [[performer]]\n|years_active = 1976\u2013present\n| associated_acts = Little Benny Blues Band, Hiroshi Sato, [[Models (band)|Models]], [[Peter Blakeley]], [[Rockmelons]], [[Kate Ceberano]], Noel's Cowards, [[Absent Friends (band)|Absent Friends]]\n|website = [http://www.wendymatthews.com/ wendymatthews.com]\n}}\n'''Wendy Joan Matthews''' (born 1960) is a Canadian-born Australian singer who has been a member of [[Models (band)|Models]] and [[Absent Friends (band)|Absent Friends]] and is a solo artist. She released Top&nbsp;20 hit singles in the 1990s including \"Token Angels\", \"Let's Kiss (Like Angels Do)\", \"The Day You Went Away\" and \"Friday's Child\" with Top&nbsp;20 albums, ''[[You've Always Got The Blues|You've Always Got the Blues]]'' (duet album with [[Kate Ceberano]]), ''[[\u00c9migr\u00e9 (album)|\u00c9migr\u00e9]]'', ''[[Lily (Wendy Matthews album)|Lily]]'', ''[[The Witness Tree]]'' and her compilation, ''[[Stepping Stones (album)|Stepping Stones]]''. She has won six [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) [[ARIA Music Awards|Awards]]. According to rock music historian, [[Ian McFarlane]] she provides \"extraordinary, crystal-clear vocals [...] a soulfulness that was the mark of a truly gifted singer\".<ref name=\"McF\"/>\n\nMatthews appeared on three series of ''[[It Takes Two (Australian TV series)|It Takes Two]]''\u2014an Australian TV celebrity singing competition\u2014partnered with [[Richard Champion]] (2006), [[Russell Gilbert]] (2007) and [[John Mangos]] (2008). On 27 October 2010, Models were inducted into the [[ARIA Hall of Fame]] by Matthews.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early years===\n{{Main|Models (band)|Rockmelons|Absent Friends (band)}}\nWendy Joan Matthews<ref name=\"ASCAP\"/> was born in 1960 in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada, with [[Abenaki people|Abenaki]] ([[First Nations]] tribe), Spanish and Scottish ancestry. Peter and Joan Matthews already had a son, Gary born a year earlier and another son, Glenn followed a year after Matthews.<ref name=\"Castro\"/> She listened and sang along to Joni Mitchell, Linda Ronstadt and Barbra Streisand records. Her parents separated when she was 14, Peter became a [[Vancouver]] advertising executive and Joan took up yoga instructing near [[Quebec City|Quebec]].<ref name=\"Castro\"/> At the age of 15 Matthews joined friends in the Little Benny Blues Band (named after Little Benny Park where they hung out). She left school at 16 and went [[busking]] across North America including south to Mexico with friends. By 1978, she was in Los Angeles where she busked, made jewellery and worked as a session singer.<ref name=\"McF\"/><ref name=\"Thompson\"/> In February 1981, Matthews sang lead vocal for \"Willow Pattern\" on [[Justin Heathcliff|Osamu Kitajima]]'s album ''Dragon King'' (1982). She met Japanese musician, Hiroshi Sato, and travelled to Japan to record lead vocals for his fourth album, ''Awakening'', which was released in June on [[Alfa Records]].<ref name=\"Sato\"/>\n\nBack in Los Angeles, Australian singer [[Glenn Shorrock]] (ex-[[Little River Band]]) asked her to provide backing vocals on his solo album ''Villain of the Peace'' (1982) and to join him on his subsequent six-week tour of Australia in 1983.<ref name=\"McF\"/><ref name=\"Castro\"/> Matthews decided to stay in Sydney at the tour's completion and found herself in demand as a session vocalist and singing jingles. She sang on albums by [[Jimmy Barnes]], [[Richard Clapton]], [[Tim Finn]] and [[Icehouse (band)|Icehouse]].<ref name=\"ARDb\"/> After singing backing vocals on [[Models (band)|Models']] 1985 album ''[[Out of Mind, Out of Sight (album)|Out of Mind, Out of Sight]]'', she became a regular vocalist for the band.<ref name=\"ARDb\"/><ref name=\"McFM\"/> Matthews and Models' guitarist and vocalist, [[Sean Kelly (Australian musician)|Sean Kelly]], had an 11-year personal relationship.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> Other backing singers for Models included [[Kate Ceberano]] and [[Zan Abeyratne]], both members of [[I'm Talking]] \u2013 the two bands often toured together.<ref name=\"McFIT\"/> In 1986, Matthews joined [[Peter Blakeley|Peter Blakeley and The Resurrection]], with Blakeley (ex-[[Rockmelons]]) on lead vocals, [[Chris Abrahams]] on bass guitar and piano (ex-The Benders), Jim Benjamin on drums and Mark Punch on guitar ([[Ren\u00e9e Geyer|Ren\u00e9e Geyer Band]]).<ref name=\"ARDb\"/> Her second album with Models, ''[[Models' Media]]'' appeared in December which reached the top&nbsp;30.<ref name=\"McFM\"/><ref name=\"Kent\"/>\n\nIn 1985, Matthews recorded vocals for the soundtrack of [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC) TV series ''Dancing Daze'' (1986) with musical production by [[Martin Armiger]].<ref name=\"DanceDaze\"/> Her tracks were, \"Dancing Daze\" (duet with [[Jenny Morris (musician)|Jenny Morris]]), \"Dare to Be Bold\", \"Might Have Been\" (trio with Morris and [[Mark Williams (singer)|Mark Williams]]) and \"Lost in a Dancing Daze\".<ref name=\"DanceDaze\"/> First three of her tracks were released as singles but neither they nor the related album, ''Dancing Daze \u2013 Rock'' reached the top&nbsp;50.<ref name=\"Kent\"/><ref name=\"DanceDaze\"/> ABC-TV and Armiger asked Matthews to sing with Ceberano on the soundtrack to the series ''Stringer'' in 1987. The soundtrack ''[[You've Always Got The Blues|You've Always Got the Blues]]'' was released as a duet album by Ceberano and Matthews in April 1988 and reached No.&nbsp;4 on the Australian [[Kent Music Report]] Albums Chart.<ref name=\"Kent\"/>\n\nMatthews was a member of Noel's Cowards, a short term project, including ex-[[Split Enz]] members [[Noel Crombie]] on drums, [[Nigel Griggs]] on bass guitar and [[Phil Judd]] on guitar.<ref name=\"ARDbNC\"/> Noel's Cowards, with Matthews on lead vocals, provided six tracks for the Australian movie ''[[Rikky and Pete]]'' (1988).<ref name=\"ARDbNC\"/> She was lead vocalist on the single \"Jump\" released in October from Rockmelons' debut album ''[[Tales of the City (album)|Tales of the City]]''.<ref name=\"McF\"/> ''Tales of the City'' peaked at No.&nbsp;14 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]].<ref name=\"AusChartsR\"/> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 1989]], Rockmelons won '[[ARIA Award for Breakthrough Artist - Album|Breakthrough Artist \u2013 Album]]' and ''Stringer'' won '[[ARIA Award for Best Original Soundtrack, Cast or Show Album|Best Original Soundtrack / Cast / Show Recording]]'.<ref name=\"ARIA1989\"/>\n\nMatthews joined the Australian supergroup, [[Absent Friends (band)|Absent Friends]], in 1989 with Kelly and [[James Valentine (Australian musician)|James Valentine]] of Models, [[Garry Gary Beers]] of [[INXS]], [[Roger Mason (musician)|Roger Mason]] and Mick King.<ref name=\"McFAF\"/> She sang lead vocals on \"I Don't Wanna Be with Nobody but You\" which reached No.&nbsp;4 on the ARIA Singles Chart; the related album, ''[[Here's Looking Up Your Address]]'' peaked at No.7.<ref name=\"AusChartsAF\"/> The band toured Australia and then supported INXS on a European tour.<ref name=\"McFAF\"/> During this period, Matthews continued her session work, singing on the [[Cher]] album ''[[Heart of Stone (Cher album)|Heart of Stone]]'' in 1989 and on Blakeley's solo album ''Harry's Cafe de Wheels'' in 1990.<ref name=\"McF\"/> Absent Friends disbanded and Matthews pursued her solo career.<ref name=\"McFAF\"/>\n\n===Solo career 1990s===\nIn 1990, Matthews recorded her debut solo album ''[[\u00c9migr\u00e9 (album)|\u00c9migr\u00e9]]'' with the assistance of Absent Friends members, Beers, Kelly, King, Mason, Valentine and [[Andrew Duffield (musician)|Andrew Duffield]] as well as Tim Finn and Blakeley.<ref name=\"McF\"/> It was produced by [[Ricky Fataar]] and released on the [[rooArt]] label owned by INXS manager, [[Chris Murphy (manager)|Chris Murphy]]; ''\u00c9migr\u00e9'' became a hit, being certified platinum.<ref name=\"McF\"/> She won the Australian ''[[Rolling Stone Australia|Rolling Stone]]'' magazine award for best female vocalist in 1990 for her debut album and her work with Absent Friends.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/>\n\nAt the [[ARIA Music Awards of 1991]], \"I Don't Wanna Be with Nobody but You\" won '[[ARIA Award for Single of the Year|Single of the Year]]' for Absent Friends; while Matthews won two [[ARIA Awards]] for '[[ARIA Award for Best Female Artist|Best Female Artist]]' and 'Breakthrough Artist \u2013 Single' for \"Token Angels\", which hit No.&nbsp;18.<ref name=\"ARIA1991\"/><ref name=\"AusCharts\"/> Subsequent hits from the album were \"Woman's Gotta Have It\" (No.&nbsp;34) and \"Let's Kiss (Like Angels Do)\" (No.&nbsp;14).<ref name=\"AusCharts\"/> Her touring band included [[Paul Abrahams (musician)|Paul Abrahams]] on bass guitar, [[Amanda Brown (musician)|Amanda Brown]] on oboe and violin (ex-[[The Go-Betweens]]), Robbie James on guitar ([[Ganggajang|GANGgajang]]), King on guitar (Absent Friends), [[Lisa Maxwell (singer, songwriter)|Lisa Maxwell]] on backing vocals, Mark Meyer on drums ([[Moving Pictures (band)|Moving Pictures]]), Mark O'Connor on keyboards and Valentine on saxophone.<ref name=\"McF\"/> On 31 May, she performed at Dallas Brooks Hall, Melbourne which was released as the live album ''[[The Way It Has to Be]]'' in October. She also supported the [[Neville Brothers]] on their Australian tour.<ref name=\"McF\"/>\n\nIn February\u2013March 1992 Matthews recorded her second solo studio album ''[[Lily (Wendy Matthews album)|Lily]]'' in Los Angeles with [[T-Bone Burnett]] producing, it was released on 28 September while she was on tour supporting [[Simply Red]].<ref name=\"McF\"/> Her album peaked at No.&nbsp;2 and achieved double-platinum in Australia selling over 140,000 copies.<ref name=\"McF\"/><ref name=\"AusCharts\"/> The lead single \"The Day You Went Away\" hit No.&nbsp;2 while the album spawned two further hits in \"Friday's Child\" (No.&nbsp;15) and \"If Only I Could\" (No.&nbsp;41).<ref name=\"AusCharts\"/> At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 1992]], Matthews was nominated for 'Best Female Artist' for her single, \"Let's Kiss (Like the Angels)\" {{sic}}.<ref name=\"ARIA1992\"/> The Canadian CD release of ''Lily'' included a French-language version of \"The Day You Went Away\".<ref name=\"ARDb\"/> Matthews toured internationally in 1993 including gigs in London, Montreal and New York.<ref name=\"Castro\"/> She won 'Best Female Artist' for ''Lily'' and both 'Best Single' and 'Highest Selling Single' for \"The Day You Went Away\" at the [[ARIA Music Awards of 1993]].<ref name=\"ARIA1993\"/> Matthews had a film role as a [[nightclub singer]] in ''Flynn'' (1993) which starred [[Guy Pearce]] as Australian-born actor [[Errol Flynn]].<ref name=\"Flynn\"/>\n\nMatthews released her next album ''[[The Witness Tree]]'' on 14 November 1994, featuring the Top 40 hit \"Standing Strong\". The album went platinum selling 100,000 copies and she won her third ARIA award for 'Best Female Artist' in [[ARIA Music Awards of 1994|1994]] for \"Friday's Child\".<ref name=\"ARIA1994\"/> In 1995, Matthews became an Australian citizen. \"Standing Strong\" won 'Most Performed Australian Work' at the [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA Awards]] of 1995.<ref name=\"APRAWin1995\"/> She returned to Canada for a visit before the release of her next album ''[[Ghosts (Wendy Matthews album)|Ghosts]]'' in 1997. The single \"Beloved\" from the album peaked at No.&nbsp;49 on the Australian charts.<ref name=\"AusCharts\"/> In 1999, Matthews released ''[[Stepping Stones (album)|Stepping Stones]]'', a greatest hits package which hit No.&nbsp;4, earning her another platinum certification.<ref name=\"ARIACred1999\"/> According to rock music historian, [[Ian McFarlane]] in his ''[[Encyclopedia of Australian Rock and Pop]]'', Matthews provides \"extraordinary, crystal-clear vocals [...] a soulfulness that was the mark of a truly gifted singer\".<ref name=\"McF\"/>\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2000, Matthews joined the cast of a new Australian musical theatre production of ''[[Godspell]]'' alongside [[Angry Anderson]], [[Jimmy Barnes]], [[Debra Byrne]], Marie Wilson, [[Fiona Horne]], [[Belinda Emmett]], [[Paul Mercurio]] and [[Terence Trent D'Arby]].<ref name=\"McF\"/> In February, with rehearsals commencing, Matthews released her cover of \"[[Day by Day (Godspell song)|Day by Day]]\" but financial difficulties prevented the musical from being staged.<ref name=\"McF\"/> She contributed \"Pure Inspiration\" to ''Olympic Record'' \u2013 an album for the [[Summer Olympics of 2000|Sydney Olympics]] by various Australian artists.<ref name=\"ARDbOR\"/>\n\nIn 2001, Matthews relocated from Sydney to a property near [[Coffs Harbour]] on the [[Mid North Coast]] of New South Wales.<ref name=\"NLACafe\"/> Her solo album, ''[[Beautiful View]]'', was released on 17 July and made the Top 40.<ref name=\"AusCharts\"/> Produced by Michael Szumowski, it was her first with [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]] records, and included three singles, \"Free\", \"Beautiful View\" and \"Like the Sun\" which did not reach the top&nbsp;50.<ref name=\"AusCharts\"/> A limited edition of ''Beautiful View'' included a bonus six-track disc.\n\nIn 2003, Matthews sang a duet with [[Rod Stewart]] on the track \"[[My Heart Stood Still]]\" on the Australian release of his album ''[[As Time Goes By: The Great American Songbook, Volume II]]''. She released her own covers album, ''[[Caf\u00e9 Naturale]]'' in May 2004.<ref name=\"NLACafe\"/> Matthews explained why she recorded it acoustically, \"To keep creative you have to break down your own personal barriers. With this record that meant moving away from pop and crafting something instrument-driven, something that feels like me playing live\".<ref name=\"Cafe\"/> The album includes acoustic versions of [[U2]]'s \"One\" from the ''[[Achtung Baby]]'' and [[Massive Attack|Massive Attack's]] \"[[Protection (Massive Attack album)|Protection]]\" from the album of the same name. The first single \"All I Need\" is a version of the [[Air (French band)|Air]] song from the ''[[Moon Safari]]'' album. Matthews' album debuted in the top 50 of the ARIA charts.\n\nMatthews embarked on the national Fallen Angels Tour during May\u2013June 2008 and then co-headlined with [[Ian Moss]] in October\u2013November. On 8 November, Matthews released the album ''[[She (Wendy Matthews album)|She]]'' on her own independent record label, Barking Bear. The album is a personal collection of favourite songs by women who have inspired her, [[Bonnie Raitt]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Chrissie Hynde]], [[Joni Mitchell]], [[Buffy Sainte-Marie]], [[Lucinda Williams]] and [[Jane Siberry]]. In June 2010, she combined with country musician, [[Adam Harvey]] for the Both Sides Tour.<ref name=\"Tripp\"/> In October 2010, Matthews performed at the Opening Ceremony of the Alice Springs Masters Games. On 27 October, her former band, Models were inducted into the [[ARIA Hall of Fame]] by Matthews.<ref name=\"ARIAHoFAAP\"/> The line-up of Duffield, Ferrie, Kelly, Mason, Price and Valentine performed \"I Hear Motion\" and \"Evolution\".<ref name=\"Treuen\"/><ref name=\"Street\"/> Matthews recalled meeting the group for the first time at a recording session \u2013 she was due to provide backing vocals but they were busy playing indoor cricket in the studio.<ref name=\"Pepper\"/>\n\nMatthews independently released ''Billie and Me: The White Room Sessions'' on 27 July 2015. The live album, available through her official website only, was recorded in the winter of 2012 with Brendan St Ledger on piano and Greg Royal on standup bass. The album celebrates the centenary year birth of Billie Holiday, who Matthews describes Holiday as an \"iconic woman whose soul and music has been long admired.\"<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://wendymatthews.com/product/billie-and-me/|title=Billie and Me|publisher=wendymatthews.com|accessdate=23 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Matthews featured on the [[Catherine Britt]] single, \"F U Cancer\" alongside [[Kasey Chambers]], [[Beccy Cole]], [[Lyn Bowtell]], [[Josh Pyke]] and [[Wes Carr]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/f-u-cancer-feat.-kasey-chambers/id1154668710|title=F U Cancer (single)|publisher=iTunes Australia|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== TV appearances ==\nMatthews has appeared on three series of [[Seven Network|Channel Seven]]'s celebrity singing competition ''[[It Takes Two (Australian television)|It Takes Two]]''. The first series premiered on 28 May 2006, she was partnered by former [[Australian Rules football]]er, [[Richard Champion]], they were voted off in week six. On 1 May 2007, ahead of the second series, Matthews, [[David Hobson (tenor)|David Hobson]] and [[Troy Cassar-Daley]] sang \"[[Got to Get You into My Life]]\" on celebrity dancing competition ''[[Dancing with the Stars (Australian season 6)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' grand final, which was won by Ceberano and her professional dance partner John Paul Collins. ''It Takes Two'' second series premiered on 8 May, where Matthews was paired with comedian [[Russell Gilbert]], they were voted off in week four of the competition. The third series commenced on 12 February 2008 with [[John Mangos]], news reader for ''[[Sky News Australia]]'', and Matthews being voted off in week two. Matthews appeared on the TV show ''[[RocKwiz]]'' on 1 November 2008, she performed Toto's \"[[Hold the Line]]\" as a duet with Johnny Galvatron from [[The Galvatrons]].\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Wendy Matthews discography}}\n*''[[You've Always Got The Blues|You've Always Got the Blues]]'' <small>(duet album with [[Kate Ceberano]])</small> (1988)\n*''[[\u00c9migr\u00e9 (album)|\u00c9migr\u00e9]]'' (1990)\n*''[[The Way It Has to Be]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Lily (Wendy Matthews album)|Lily]]'' (1992)\n*''[[The Witness Tree]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Ghosts (Wendy Matthews album)|Ghosts]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Beautiful View]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Caf\u00e9 Naturale]]'' (2004)\n*''[[She (Wendy Matthews album)|She]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[The Welcome Fire]]'' (2013)\n* ''Billie and Me: The White Room Sessions'' (2015)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===APRA Awards===\nThe [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA Awards]] are presented annually from 1982 by the [[Australasian Performing Right Association]] (APRA).<ref name=\"APRAMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History.aspx |title=APRA History |publisher=[[Australasian Performing Right Association]] (APRA) |accessdate=31 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920230857/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History.aspx |archivedate=20 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 1995 || \"Standing Strong\" \u2013 (Wendy Matthews, Glenn Skinner) || Most Performed Australian Work<ref name=\"APRAWin1995\">{{cite web|url=http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/1995Winners.aspx |title=1995 Winners \u2013 APRA Music Awards |publisher=Australasian Performing Right Association (APRA) |accessdate=31 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308005511/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/APRAAwards/MusicAwards/History/1995Winners.aspx |archivedate=8 March 2011 }}</ref> || {{won}}\n|-\n\n{{end}}\n\n===ARIA Awards===\nThe [[ARIA Music Awards]] are presented annually from 1987 by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA). Matthews has won six awards from sixteen nominations as a solo artist.<ref name=\"ARIAWM\"/>\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1989|1989]] || rowspan=\"3\"| ''[[You've Always Got The Blues]]'' || [[ARIA Award for Best Female Artist|Best Female Artist]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n|| [[ARIA Award for Best Adult Contemporary Album|Best Adult Contemporary Album]] (with Kate Ceberano) || {{nom}}\n|-\n|| Best Jazz Album (with Kate Ceberano) || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1991|1991]] || rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[\u00c9migr\u00e9 (album)|\u00c9migr\u00e9]]'' || Best Female Artist<ref name=\"ARIA1991\"/> || {{won}}\n|-\n|| Breakthrough Artist \u2013 Album || {{nom}}\n|-\n|| \"[[Token Angels]]\" || Breakthrough Artist \u2013 Single<ref name=\"ARIA1991\"/> || {{won}}\n|-\n| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1992|1992]] || \"Let's Kiss (Like the Angels)\"{{sic|}} || Best Female Artist<ref name=\"ARIA1992\"/> || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1993|1993]] ||rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Lily (Wendy Matthews album)|Lily]]'' || [[ARIA Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]<ref name=\"ARIA1993\"/> || {{nom}}\n|-\n|| Best Female Artist<ref name=\"ARIA1993\"/> || {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| \"[[The Day You Went Away]]\" || [[ARIA Award for Single of the Year|Single of the Year]]<ref name=\"ARIA1993\"/> || {{won}}\n|-\n|| Highest Selling Single<ref name=\"ARIA1993\"/> || {{won}}\n|-\n|| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1994|1994]] || \"Friday's Child\" || Best Female Artist<ref name=\"ARIA1994\"/> || {{won}}\n|-\n|| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1995|1995]] || ''[[The Witness Tree]]'' || Best Adult Contemporary Album<ref name=\"ARIA1995\"/> || {{nom}}\n|-\n|| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1997|1997]] || \"Then I Walked Away\" || Best Female Artist<ref name=\"ARIA1997\"/> || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1998|1998]] || ''[[Ghosts (Wendy Matthews album)|Ghosts]]'' || Best Adult Contemporary Album<ref name=\"ARIA1998\"/> || {{nom}}\n|-\n| ''Ghosts'' except \"Halcyon Days\" \u2013 Tony Espie || Engineer of the Year<ref name=\"ARIA1998\"/> || {{nom}}\n|-\n|| [[ARIA Music Awards of 2001|2001]] || ''[[Beautiful View]]'' || Best Adult Contemporary Album<ref name=\"ARIA2001\"/> || {{nom}}\n\n{{end}}\n\nMatthews has also won awards as a member of groups ([[Absent Friends (band)|Absent Friends]],<ref name=\"ARIAAF\"/> [[Rockmelons]])<ref name=\"ARIAAR\"/> and projects (''Stringers'' soundtrack album, ''You've Always Got the Blues \u2013 Songs from the ABC TV Series \"Stringer\"'').<ref name=\"ARIAAVar\"/>\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1989|1989]] || ''[[Tales of the City (album)|Tales of the City]]'' || [[ARIA Award for Breakthrough Artist - Album|Breakthrough Artist \u2013 Album]]<ref name=\"ARIA1989\"/> || {{won}}\n|-\n| ''Stringer'' \u2013 various artists ([[Kate Ceberano]], Matthews, [[Martin Armiger]], [[Joy Smithers]])<ref name=\"Stringer\"/> || [[ARIA Award for Best Original Soundtrack, Cast or Show Album|Best Original Soundtrack / Cast / Show Recording]]<ref name=\"ARIA1989\"/> || {{won}}\n|-\n| [[ARIA Music Awards of 1991|1991]] || \"[[I Don't Want to Be with Nobody but You|(I Don't Want to Be With) Nobody but You]] \u2013 [[Absent Friends (band)|Absent Friends]] || Single of the Year<ref name=\"ARIA1991\"/> || {{won}}\n\n{{end}}\n\n===Other awards===\n*1990 ''[[Rolling Stone Australia|Rolling Stone]]'', 'Best Female Vocalist'.<ref name=\"Taylor\"/>\n*1991 [[Mo Awards]], 'Female Rock Performer'.<ref name=\"Mo1991\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n;General\n\n*{{cite encyclopedia|last=McFarlane |first=Ian |authorlink=Ian McFarlane |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia of Australian Rock and Pop]] |title=Whammo Homepage |url=//www.whammo.com.au/index.asp |accessdate=22 July 2010 |year=1999 |publisher=[[Allen & Unwin]] |location=[[St Leonards, New South Wales|St Leonards, NSW]] |isbn=1-86508-072-1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040405231007/http://www.whammo.com.au/index.asp |archivedate=5 April 2004 }} Note: Archived on-line copy has limited functionality.\n*{{cite book|title=The Who's Who of Australian Rock|last=Spencer|first=Chris|author2=Zbig Nowara |author3=Paul McHenry |origyear=1987|year=2002|publisher=Five Mile Press|location=[[Noble Park, Victoria|Noble Park]], Vic.|page=|isbn=1-86503-891-1}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/2090055|title=Who's who of Australian rock / compiled by Chris Spencer, Zbig Nowara & Paul McHenry|work=catalogue|publisher